# Android SDK Location Configuration
# Copy this file to 'local.properties' and update the sdk.dir path

# =============================================================================
# WINDOWS USERS - Choose one of these common Android SDK locations:
# =============================================================================

# Option 1: Android Studio default location (most common)
# sdk.dir=C\:\\Users\\YourUsername\\AppData\\Local\\Android\\Sdk

# Option 2: If you installed Android Studio in custom location
# sdk.dir=C\:\\Android\\Sdk

# Option 3: If you're using Android SDK command line tools
# sdk.dir=C\:\\android-sdk

# =============================================================================
# LINUX/MAC USERS - Choose one of these common locations:
# =============================================================================

# Linux default
# sdk.dir=/home/yourusername/Android/Sdk

# Mac default  
# sdk.dir=/Users/yourusername/Library/Android/sdk

# =============================================================================
# HOW TO FIND YOUR ANDROID SDK PATH:
# =============================================================================

# Method 1: Android Studio
# 1. Open Android Studio
# 2. Go to File > Settings (Windows) or Android Studio > Preferences (Mac)
# 3. Go to Appearance & Behavior > System Settings > Android SDK
# 4. Copy the "Android SDK Location" path

# Method 2: Command Line
# Windows: echo %ANDROID_HOME%
# Linux/Mac: echo $ANDROID_HOME

# Method 3: Check common locations manually:
# Windows: C:\Users\%USERNAME%\AppData\Local\Android\Sdk
# Linux: ~/Android/Sdk
# Mac: ~/Library/Android/sdk

# =============================================================================
# INSTRUCTIONS:
# =============================================================================
# 1. Copy this file to 'local.properties' (remove .example)
# 2. Uncomment and update ONE of the sdk.dir lines above
# 3. Replace 'YourUsername' with your actual Windows username
# 4. Use double backslashes (\\) for Windows paths
# 5. Save the file

# Example for user "Seif" on Windows:
# sdk.dir=C\:\\Users\\Seif\\AppData\\Local\\Android\\Sdk